Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Trim and thinly slice the @spring onion{1}(trimmed and thinly sliced). Halve any large @broccoli florets{200%g}.

Zest and halve the @lime{1/2}(zested and halved).

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated).

Pour the cold @water{300%ml} into a #medium saucepan{} with a #tight-fitting lid{}.

Stir in the @Jasmine rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Lay the @sea bass fillets{2} onto a lined #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}, then spread the garlic over each fillet.

When the oven is hot, bake the fish on the top shelf for ~{5%minutes}, then pour half the @teriyaki sauce{75%ml} over the fish. Return to the oven to bake until cooked through, ~{7-10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw fish. The fish is cooked when opaque in the middle.

While the fish bakes, pour the remaining teriyaki into a #small bowl{} and squeeze in the lime juice.

Mix together and set aside.

Pop the (now empty) #frying pan{} on medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{}.

Once hot, stir-fry the broccoli for ~{2-3%minutes}, then add a splash of water and immediately cover with a #lid{} or some #foil{}.

Allow to cook until the broccoli is tender, ~{4-5%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}.

When everything is ready, remove the fish from the oven and spoon over the teriyaki sauce.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{}, then stir through the lime zest and spoon into your bowls. Top with the teriyaki sea bass and all the sauce from the tray.

Serve the broccoli alongside and finish with a scattering of spring onions and toasted @roasted white sesame seeds{7}.

Enjoy!